07190nam a22008655i 9780887559228DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2020448136  a97808875592287 a10.1515/97808875592282doi  a(DE-B1597)664667  a(OCoLC)1243554877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA00aP94.5.I532bC2164 2021 4aP94.5.I532bC25 2021 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a305.5/20899707122300aIndigenous Celebrity :bEntanglements with Fame /ced. by Robert Alexander Innes, Jennifer Adese. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIndigeneity, Celebrity, and Fame: Accounting for Colonialism -- tMino-Waawiindaganeziwin: What Does Indigenous Celebrity Mean within Anishinaabeg Contexts? -- tEmpowering Voices from the Past: The Playing Experiences of Retired Pasifika Rugby League Athletes in Australia -- tMy Mom, the “Military Mohawk Princess”: kahntinetha1 Horn through the Lens of Indigenous Female Celebrity -- tIndigenous Activism and Celebrity: Negotiating Access, Inclusion, and the Politics of Humility -- tRags-to-Riches and Other Fairytales: Indigenous Celebrity in Australia 1950–80 -- t“Pretty Boy” Trudeau Versus the “Algonquin Agitator”: Hitting the Ropes of Canadian Colonialist Masculinities -- tFamous “Last” Speakers: Celebrity and Erasure in Media Coverage of Indigenous Language Endangerment -- tCelebrity in Absentia: Situating the Indigenous People of the Andaman and Nicobar Islands in the Indian Social Imaginary -- tMarvin Rainwater and “The Pale Faced Indian”: How Cover Songs Appropriated a Story of Cultural Appropriation -- tCollectivity as Indigenous Anti-Celebrity: Global Indigeneity and the Indigenous Rights Movement -- tMakings, Meanings, and Recognitions: The Stuff of Anishinaabe Stars -- tAcknowledgements -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndigenous Celebrity speaks to the possibilities, challenges, and consequences of popular forms of recognition, critically recasting the lens through which we understand Indigenous people’s entanglements with celebrity. It presents a wide range of essays that explore the theoretical, material, social, cultural, and political impacts of celebrity on and for Indigenous people. It questions and critiques the whitestream concept of celebrity and the very juxtaposition of “Indigenous” and “celebrity” and casts a critical lens on celebrity culture’s impact on Indigenous people. Indigenous people who willingly engage with celebrity culture, or are drawn up into it, enter into a complex terrain of social relations informed by layered dimensions of colonialism, racism, sexism, homophobia/transphobia, and classism. Yet this reductive framing of celebrity does not account for the ways that Indigenous people’s own worldviews inform Indigenous engagement with celebrity culture––or rather, popular social and cultural forms of recognition. Indigenous Celebrity reorients conversations on Indigenous celebrity towards understanding how Indigenous people draw from nation-specific processes of respect and recognition while at the same time navigating external assumptions and expectations. This collection examines the relationship of Indigenous people to the concept of celebrity in past, present, and ongoing contexts, identifying commonalities, tensions, and possibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCelebrities in mass media. 0aCelebritieszCanada. 0aFame. 0aIndigenous peoples and mass mediazCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAnishinaabeg.  aAppropriation.  aAustralia.  aMasculinities.1 aAdair, Daryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdese, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdese, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnderson, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaudhury, Aadita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Jenny L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiacona, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Jonathan G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHokowhitu, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn-Miller, Kahente, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInnes, Robert Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInnes, Robert Alexander, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLakisa, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightfoot, Sheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazinegiizhigoo-kwe Bédard, Renée E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLaurin, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSy, w. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeaiwa, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.